1. Introduction to HTML
What is HTML?

HTML (HyperText Markup Language) is the standard markup language used to create and structure web pages.

HTML defines the structure of web content.
It tells browsers how content should be displayed.
HTML is not a programming language.
It is a markup language consisting of elements and tags.
Full Form

Hyper Text Markup Language

Meaning of HyperText

HyperText refers to text that contains links connecting one document to another.

Example:

<a href="https://google.com">Google</a>

Clicking the text redirects users to another page.

Meaning of Markup Language

A markup language uses tags to define elements within a document.

Example:

<h1>Heading</h1>

The tag tells the browser that the content is a heading.

2. History of HTML
Version	Year	Features
HTML 1.0	1991	Basic structure
HTML 2.0	1995	Standardized HTML
HTML 3.2	1997	Tables, scripting
HTML 4.01	1999	Improved forms
XHTML	2000	XML-based HTML
HTML5	2014	Multimedia, APIs
Living Standard	Current	Continuous updates
3. Features of HTML
Easy to learn
Platform independent
Free and open standard
Supports multimedia
Supports hyperlinks
Integrates with CSS and JavaScript
SEO friendly
Semantic structure support
4. Structure of HTML Document

Basic Structure:

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Page Title</title>
</head>
<body>

</body>
</html>
Components
1. DOCTYPE Declaration
<!DOCTYPE html>
Declares document type.
Tells browser to use HTML5 standards.
2. html Tag
<html>

Root element containing entire webpage.

3. head Tag

Contains metadata:

<head>
</head>

Not displayed on webpage.

4. body Tag

Contains visible content.

<body>
</body>
5. HTML Elements

An HTML element consists of:

<tagname>Content</tagname>

Example:

<p>Hello</p>
Empty Elements

Elements with no closing tags.

Examples:

<br>
<hr>
<img>
<input>
<meta>
<link>
6. HTML Tags

Tags are keywords enclosed in angle brackets.

<h1>Heading</h1>
Types of Tags
Container Tags

Require opening and closing tags.

<p>Text</p>
Empty Tags

No closing tag.

<br>
7. HTML Attributes

Provide additional information about elements.

Syntax:

<tag attribute="value">

Example:

<img src="image.jpg">
Common Attributes
Attribute	Purpose
id	Unique identifier
class	Group elements
style	Inline CSS
title	Tooltip
href	Link URL
src	Resource source
alt	Alternative text
target	Link behavior
disabled	Disable element
readonly	Read only
required	Mandatory field
8. HTML Head Section

Contains metadata.

Example:

<head>
<title>My Website</title>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
</head>
Important Head Elements
Title
<title>Home</title>
Meta
<meta charset="UTF-8">

Defines character encoding.

Link
<link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">

Connects external CSS.

Script
<script src="script.js"></script>

Connects JavaScript.

9. Headings

HTML provides six heading levels.

<h1>
<h2>
<h3>
<h4>
<h5>
<h6>

Importance:

h1 → Most important
h6 → Least important
